[[File:Tagetes lucida MHNT.BOT.2011.3.90.jpg|thumb|''Tagetes lucida'' - [[MHNT]]]]

'''''Tagetes lucida''''' is a perennial plant native to [[Mexico]] and [[Central America]].  It is used as a medicinal plant and as a culinary [[herb]].  The leaves have a tarragon-like flavor, with hints of [[anise]], and it has entered the nursery trade in North America as a [[tarragon]] substitute.  Common names include  '''Mexican marigold''', '''peric<U+00F3>n''', '''Mexican mint marigold''', '''Mexican tarragon''', '''Spanish tarragon''', '''Cempax<U+00F3>chitl''' and '''Texas tarragon'''.

==Description==
Pericon grows 18-30 in (46<U+2013>76&nbsp;cm) tall. Depending on land race, the plant may be fairly upright, while other forms appear bushy with many unbranching stems. The leaves are linear to oblong, about 3 in (7.6&nbsp;cm) long, and shiny medium green, not blue-green as in French tarragon (''Artemisia dracunculus'' var. ''sativa'').  In late summer it bears clusters of small golden yellow flower heads on the ends of the stems.  The flower heads are about 0.5 in (1.3&nbsp;cm) across and have 3-5 golden-yellow ray florets.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.floridata.com/ref/t/tage_luc.cfm |first=Steve |last=Christman |title=#614 Tagetes lucida |publisher=Floridata |date=2004-02-27}}</ref> The flowers are hermaphroditic (have both male and female organs) and are pollinated by insects.<ref name="PFAF">{{cite web |url=http://www.pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Tagetes+lucida |title=Tagetes lucida - Cav. |publisher=Plants For A Future}}</ref>

==Uses==

Fresh or dried leaves are used as a tarragon substitute for flavoring soups, sauces etc. 

A pleasant anise-flavored tea is brewed using the dried leaves and flowering tops.This is primarily used medicinally in Mexico and Central America. 
 
A yellow dye can be obtained from the flowers. 

The dried plant is burnt as an incense and to repel insects.<ref name="PFAF"/>

''Tagetes lucida'' was used by the [[Aztecs]] in their ritual [[incense]] known as Yauhtli.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.entheology.org/edoto/anmviewer.asp?a=279|title=Tagetes lucida - Marigolds- Americas to Argentina|work=Entheology|accessdate=2008-08-30}}</ref> Aztecs used Tagete lucida was allegedly used as a medicine they blew a powder on the face of victims before the sacrifice.The plants was linked to the rain's god [[Tlaloc]].<ref>Michel Graulich, Le Sacrifice humain chez les Azt<U+00E8>ques Paris, Fayard, 2005</ref>  <U+00A8>
The plant is also used by the [[Huichol people|Huichol]], mixed with ''[[Nicotiana rustica]]'' (a potent wild tobacco), for its claimed [[psychotropic]] and [[entheogen]]ic effects.<ref name=Okun>{{cite book|last=Okun|first=Ronald|title=Pharmacology & Toxicology Annual Review|publisher=Annual Reviews, Incorporated|year=1977|pages=656|isbn=978-0-8243-0417-1}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Schultes|first=Richard Evans|coauthors=[[Siri von Reis]]|title=Ethnobotany: evolution of a discipline|publisher=Timber Press|year=1995|pages=382|isbn=978-0-931146-28-2}}</ref>

In one study, [[methanol]]ic extract from the flower inhibited growth of ''[[Staphylococcus aureus]]'', ''[[E. coli]]'', and ''[[Candida albicans]]'' cultures-an effect that was enhanced with exposure to ultraviolet light.  The roots, stems, and leaves also had the same effect when irradiated with [[Ultraviolet|UV]] light.<ref>{{cite book|last=Nader|first=Laura|title=Naked Science: Anthropological Inquiry Into Boundaries, Power, and Knowledge|publisher=Routledge|year=1996|pages=61|isbn=978-0-415-91465-9}}</ref>

==Phytochemistry==
The plant contains the following compounds:
*[[Anethole]]<ref name=Bicchi>{{cite journal|last=Bicchi|first=Carlo|coauthors=et al.|date=1998-12-04|title=Constituents of Tagetes lucida Cav. ssp. lucida Essential Oil|journal=Flavour and Fragrance Journal|publisher=John Wiley & Sons, Ltd.|volume=12|issue=1|pages=47<U+2013>52|doi=10.1002/(SICI)1099-1026(199701)12:1<47::AID-FFJ610>3.0.CO;2-7}}</ref>
*[[Chavicol]]<ref>{{cite journal |author=Cicci<U+00F3> JF |title=A source of almost pure methyl chavicol: volatile oil from the aerial parts of Tagetes lucida (Asteraceae) cultivated in Costa Rica |journal=Rev. Biol. Trop. |volume=52 |issue=4 |pages=853<U+2013>7 |year=2004 |month=December |pmid=17354394 |doi= |url=}}</ref>
*[[Coumarin]]<ref name=Okun/>
*[[Estragole]]<ref name=Bicchi/>
*[[Isorhamnetin]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Bohm|first=Bruce A.|coauthors=Tod F. Stuessy|title=Flavonoids of the sunflower family (Asteraceae) |publisher=Springer|year=2007|pages=597|isbn=978-3-211-83479-4}}</ref>
*[[Methyleugenol]]<ref name=Bicchi/>
*[[Quercitin]]<ref name=Okun/>

